e":"1330–Afdød","1335–1399":"1335–1399","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Bef 1340":"før 1340","Bef 1351":"før 1351","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","about 1315":"omkring 1315","1364":"1364","about 1335":"1335","Netherlands":"Nederlandene","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene","Dinther, Gemeente Bernheze, North Brabant, Nederland":"Dinther, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene","Middelrode, North Brabant":"Middelrode, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene"},"nl":{"1290–Bef 1351":"1290–vóór 1351","1280–1351":"1280–1351","1290–1351":"1290–1351","1310–Male":"1310–Overleden","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1315–1399":"1315–1399","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1335–1399":"1335–1399","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Bef 1340":"vóór 1340","Bef 1351":"vóór 1351","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","about 1315":"circa 1315","1364":"1364","about 1335":"1335","Netherlands":"Nederland","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Dinther, Gemeente Bernheze, North Brabant, Nederland":"Dinther, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Middelrode, North Brabant":"Middelrode, Noord-Brabant, Nederland"},"en":{"1290–Bef 1351":"1290–before 1351","1280–1351":"1280–1351","1290–1351":"1290–1351","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1315–1399":"1315–1399","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1335–1399":"1335–1399","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Bef 1340":"before 1340","Bef 1351":"before 1351","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","about 1315":"about 1315","1364":"1364","about 1335":"1335","Netherlands":"Netherlands","North Brabant, Netherlands":"North Brabant, Netherlands","Dinther, Gemeente Bernheze, North Brabant, Nederland":"Dinther, North Brabant, Netherlands","Middelrode, North Brabant":"Middelrode, North Brabant, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Moenle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Grete, Heinz, Orlo, Otto.","North German (<b>Möhle</b>): topographic name for someone living near a mill, or a metonymic occupational name for a miller or worker in a mill, from Middle Low German <i>mole</i> ‘mill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mohl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erhardt, Ewald, Juergen, Otto, Reinhard.","North German (<b>Möhl</b>): variant of   Moehle  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): possibly from Hebrew <i>mohel</i>, an occupational name meaning ‘circumciser’."]}]},{"name":"Elisabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."],"variants":[{"name":"Elizabeth","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."]}]},{"name":"Arnoud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Arnold</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Elisabeth Arnoud van Moenle van HINTHAM was born in 1290, in Netherlands as the daughter of Arnoud Arnoud van Moenle van HINTHAM. She married Dirk Wouter Jan van Boechem. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died before 1351."},"et":{"1290–Bef 1351":"1290–enne 1351","1280–1351":"1280–1351","1290–1351":"1290–1351","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1315–1399":"1315–1399","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1335–1399":"1335–1399","1280–1340":"1280–1340","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1351":"1351","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Bef 1340":"enne 1340","Bef 1351":"enne 1351","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1364":"1364","about 1335":"1335","Netherlands":"Madalmaad","North Brabant, Netherlands":"Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Dinther, Gemeente Bernheze, North Brabant, Nederland":"Dinther, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Middelrode, North Brabant":"Middelrode, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad"},"fi":{"1290–Bef 1351":"1290–ennen vuotta 1351","1280–1351":"1280–1351","1290–1351":"1290–1351","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1315–1399":"1315–1399","1330–Male"